{"title_page": "Jim Peebles", "text_new": "{{about||the American football player|Jim Peebles (American football)|the Australian rugby league player|Jim Peebles (rugby league)}}\n{{short description|Canadian-American astrophysicist and cosmologist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = James Peebles\n|honorific_suffix  = {{post-nominals|country=CAN|OM|FRS|size=100%}}\n|image             = Jim Peebles 2010.jpg\n|caption           = Peebles in 2010\n|birth_name        = Phillip James Edwin Peebles\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1935|4|25}}\n|birth_place       = [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], [[Canada]]\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|nationality       = [[Canada|Canadian]], [[United States|American]]\n|education         = [[University of Manitoba]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])}}<br />[[Princeton University]] {{small|([[Master of Science|MS]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n|known_for         = [[Cosmic microwave background radiation]]<br>[[Cosmic\n|workplaces        = [[Princeton University]]<br />[[Institute for Advanced Study]]\n|thesis_title      = Observational tests and theoretical problems relating to the conjecture that the strength of the electromagnetic interaction may be variable\n|thesis_url        = https://search.proquest.com/docview/302111786/\n|thesis_year       = 1962\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Robert Dicke]]\n|academic_advisors = \n|doctoral_students = {{ublist|[[Margaret J. Geller]]|[[Stuart L. Shapiro]]}}\n|notable_students  = \n}}\n\n'''Phillip James Edwin Peebles''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|OM|FRS}} (born April 25, 1935) is a [[Canada|Canadian]]-[[United States|American]] [[astrophysicist]], astronomer, and theoretical [[physical cosmology|cosmologist]] who is currently the Albert Einstein Professor Emeritus of Science at [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princeton.edu/physics/about-us/history/memorable-members/john-wheeler/ |title=Princeton University Physics Department |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511222857/http://www.princeton.edu/physics/about-us/history/memorable-members/john-wheeler/ |archive-date=May 11, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.princeton.edu/main/news/archive/A94/84/71G20/index.xml |title=Princeton University News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413193815/https://www.princeton.edu/main/news/archive/A94/84/71G20/index.xml |archive-date=April 13, 2016 }}</ref> He is widely regarded as one of the world's leading [[theoretical cosmology|theoretical cosmologists]] in the period since 1970, with major theoretical contributions to [[primordial nucleosynthesis]], [[dark matter]], the [[cosmic microwave background]], and [[structure formation]]. \n\nPeebles was awarded half of the [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] in 2019 for his theoretical discoveries in [[physical cosmology]].<ref name=\"SA-20191012\">{{cite news |last=Hooper |first=Dan |title=A Well-Deserved Physics Nobel - Jim Peebles' award honors modern cosmological theory at last |url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/observations/a-well-deserved-physics-nobel/ |date=October 12, 2019 |work=[[Scientific American]] |accessdate=October 13, 2019 }}</ref> He shared the prize with [[Michel Mayor]] and [[Didier Queloz]] for their discovery of an exoplanet orbiting a sun-like star.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2019/summary/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physics 2019|publisher= [[Nobel Media AB]]|accessdate= October 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20191008\">{{cite news |last1=Chang |first1=Kenneth |last2=Specia |first2=Megan |title=Nobel Prize in Physics Awarded for Cosmic Discoveries - The cosmologist James Peebles split the prize with the astrophysicists Michel Mayor and Didier Queloz, for work the Nobel judges said \"transformed our ideas about the cosmos.\" |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/08/science/nobel-prize-physics.html |date=October 8, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 8, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaplan |first1=Sarah |title=Nobel Prize in physics awarded for research on exoplanets and the structure of the universe |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2019/10/08/nobel-prize-physics-awarded-research-exoplanets-structure-universe/?wpisrc=nl_optimist&wpmm=1 |accessdate=13 October 2019 |work=Washington Post |date=8 October 2019}}</ref> In his award presentation, Peebles noted that he does not prefer the term \"[[Big Bang|Big Bang Theory]]\", since \"it connotes the notion of an event and a position, both of which are quite wrong.\"  While much of his work relates to the development of the universe from its first few seconds, he is more skeptical about what we can know about the very beginning, and stated, \"It's very unfortunate that one thinks of the beginning whereas in fact, we have no good theory of such a thing as the beginning.\"<ref name=\"PHY-20191114\">{{cite news |last=Couronne |first=Ivan |title=Top cosmologist's lonely battle against 'Big Bang' theory |url=https://phys.org/news/2019-11-cosmologist-lonely-big-theory.html |date=November 14, 2019 |work=[[Phys.org]] |accessdate=November 14, 2019 }}</ref>\n\nPeebles has described himself as a convinced [[agnosticism|agnostic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aip.org/history-programs/niels-bohr-library/oral-histories/25507-2|title=Jim Peebles - Session II|date=2015-04-01|website=www.aip.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPeebles was born on April 25, 1935 in [[St. Boniface, Winnipeg|St. Boniface]], in present-day [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], [[Canada]], the son of Ada Marion (Green), a homemaker, and Andrew Charles Peebles, who worked for the [[Winnipeg Grain Exchange]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=piQvAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Andrew+Charles+Peebles%22&dq=%22Andrew+Charles+Peebles%22 |title=Notable Scientists from 1900 to the Present |volume=4 (N\u2013S) |editor-first=Brigham |editor-last=Narins |publisher=Gale Group |year=2001 |edition=2 |isbn=9780787617554 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> He completed his bachelor of science at the [[University of Manitoba]]. He left Manitoba in the fall of 1958 to attend [[Princeton University]], where he received his [[Ph.D.]] in 1962<ref>{{cite web |work=science.ca |url=http://www.science.ca/scientists/scientistprofile.php?pID=205 |title=Phillip James E. Peebles Astronomy, Astrophysics and Space Science |date=October 8, 2019 |access-date=October 8, 2019 |publisher=GCS Research Society}}</ref><ref name=\"thesis-peebles-1962\">{{cite thesis |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/302111786/ |title=Observational tests and theoretical problems relating to the conjecture that the strength of the electromagnetic interaction may be variable |date=1962 |publisher=[[Princeton University]] |degree=Ph.D. |last=Peebles |first=Phillip James Edwin |via=[[ProQuest]] |url-access=subscription |oclc=83718695}}</ref> under the supervision of physicist [[Robert Dicke]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Seeing Cosmology Grow |journal=[[Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics]] |volume=50 |year=2012 |pages=1\u201328 |first=P.J.E. |last=Peebles |doi=10.1146/annurev-astro-081811-125526|bibcode=2012ARA&A..50....1P }}</ref> He remained at Princeton for his whole career. Peebles was a Member in the School of Natural Sciences at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]] during the academic year 1977\u201378; he made subsequent visits during 1990\u201391 and 1998\u201399.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ias.edu/scholars/phillip-james-e-peebles|title=Phillip James E. Peebles|website=[[Institute for Advanced Study]]|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nMost of Peebles' work since 1964 has been in the field of [[physical cosmology]] to determine the origins of the universe. In 1964, there was very little interest in this field and it was considered a \"dead end\" but Peebles remained committed to studying it.<ref name=\"princeton nobel\">{{cite web | url = https://www.princeton.edu/news/2019/10/08/joy-ride-career-peebles-wins-nobel-prize-physics-tackling-big-questions-about | title =  A 'joy ride' of a career: Peebles wins Nobel Prize in Physics for tackling big questions about the universe | first = Tom | last = Garlinghouse | date = October 8, 2019 | accessdate = October 9, 2019 | publisher = [[Princeton University]] }}</ref> Peebles has made many important contributions to the [[Big Bang]] model. With Dicke and others (nearly two decades after [[George Gamow]], [[Ralph A. Alpher]] and [[Robert Herman|Robert C. Herman]]), Peebles predicted the [[cosmic microwave background radiation]]. Along with making major contributions to [[Big Bang nucleosynthesis]], [[dark matter]], and [[dark energy]], he was the leading pioneer in the theory of cosmic [[structure formation]] in the 1970s. Long before it was considered a serious, quantitative branch of physics, Peebles was studying physical cosmology and has done much to establish its respectability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ias.edu/ideas/2015/thomas-general-relativity|title=General Relativity's Influence and Mysteries|website=Institute for Advanced Study|language=en|access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref> Peebles said, \"It was not a single step, some critical discovery that suddenly made cosmology relevant but the field gradually emerged through a number of experimental observations. Clearly one of the most important during my career was the detection of the cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation that immediately attracted attention [...] both experimentalists interested in measuring the properties of this radiation and theorists, who joined in analyzing the implications\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ep-news.web.cern.ch/content/interview-james-peebles|title=Interview with James Peebles|website= CERN EP newsletter|language=en|access-date=May 4, 2016}}</ref>  His Shaw Prize citation states \"He laid the foundations for almost all modern investigations in cosmology, both theoretical and observational, transforming a highly speculative field into a precision science.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=53&threeid=67&fourid=123|title=Announcement-The Shaw Laureate in Astronomy 2004|publisher=Shaw Foundation|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPeebles has a long record of innovating the basic ideas, which would be extensively studied later by other scientists. For instance, in 1987, he proposed the [[primordial isocurvature baryon model]] for the development of the early universe.<ref>Hu (June 28, 1994)</ref> Similarly, Peebles contributed to establishing the dark matter problem in the early 1970s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=de Swart|first1=J. G.|last2=Bertone|first2=G. |last3=van Dongen|first3=J. |title=How dark matter came to matter|journal=[[Nature Astronomy]] |date=2017|volume=1|issue=3 |pages=0059|id=[https://www.nature.com/articles/s41550-017-0059 0059] |doi=10.1038/s41550-017-0059|arxiv = 1703.00013 |bibcode = 2017NatAs...1E..59D }}</ref> Peebles is also known for the [[Ostriker\u2013Peebles criterion]], relating to the stability of [[Galaxy formation and evolution|galactic formation]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=01yNf7mipb0C&pg=PA374|title=Galactic Dynamics |last=Binney|first=James |last2=Tremaine|first2=Scott |date=1987|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691084459|pages=374|language=en}}</ref> \n\nPeebles' body of work was recognized with him being named a 2019 Nobel Laureate in Physics, \"for theoretical discoveries in physical cosmology\"; Peebles shared half the prize with [[Michel Mayor]] and [[Didier Queloz]] who had been the first to discover an [[exoplanet]] around a [[main sequence]] star.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/08/science/nobel-physics.html | title = Nobel Prize in Physics Awarded for Studies of Earth's Place in the Universe | first1 = Kenneth | last1 = Chang | first2 = Megan | last2 = Specia | date = October 8, 2019 | accessdate = October 9, 2019 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n; Awards\n{{div col |colwidth=35em}}\n* [[Fellow of the American Physical Society]] (1964)<ref>{{cite web|title=APS Fellow Archive|url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/fellowships/archive-all.cfm?initial=&year=1964&unit_id=&institution=Princeton+University}}</ref>\n* [[Eddington Medal]] (1981)<ref name=Weintraub>{{cite book |last1=Weintraub |first1=David A. |title=How Old Is the Universe? |date=2011 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=9780691147314 |page=317 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oWmGcsV7N6sC |accessdate=October 8, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Dannie Heineman Prize for Astrophysics|Heineman Prize]] (1982)<ref>{{cite web |title=Dannie Heineman Prize for Astrophysics {{!}} American Astronomical Society |url=https://aas.org/grants-and-prizes/dannie-heineman-prize-astrophysics |website=aas.org |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (1982)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/phillip-peebles-12070/|title=Phillip Peebles biography|publisher= [[Royal Society]]|accessdate= January 24, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Norris Russell Lectureship]] (1993)<ref name=Weintraub />\n* [[Bruce Medal]] (1995)<ref>{{cite web |title=The Bruce Medalists |url=http://www.phys-astro.sonoma.edu/brucemedalists/ |website=www.phys-astro.sonoma.edu |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Oskar Klein Memorial Lecture|Oskar Klein Medal]] (1997)<ref>{{cite web |title=Earlier Lectures - Oskar Klein Centre |url=http://www.okc.albanova.se/research/memorial-lecture/earlier-lectures |website=www.okc.albanova.se |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society]] (1998)<ref>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=D. A. |title=Prof. P J E Peebles: 1998 Gold Medal |url=https://academic.oup.com/astrogeo/article/40/3/3.6/197418/ |journal=Astronomy & Geophysics |volume=40 |issue=3 |accessdate=October 8, 2019 |pages=3.6\u2013a\u20133.6 |language=en |doi=10.1093/astrog/40.3.3.6-a |date=June 1, 1999}}</ref>\n* [[Gruber Prize in Cosmology]] (2000), with [[Allan Sandage]]<ref>{{cite web |title=2000 Gruber Cosmology Prize {{!}} Gruber Foundation |url=https://gruber.yale.edu/prize/2000-gruber-cosmology-prize |website=gruber.yale.edu |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Harvey Prize]] (2001)<ref>{{cite web |title=Princeton Announcements, June 2001 - Archived |url=http://www.princeton.edu/webannounce/Princeton_Announcements/Archived/2001/JUN_Text.html |website=www.princeton.edu |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Shaw Prize]] (2004)<ref>{{cite web |title=The Shaw Prize - Top prizes for astronomy, life science and mathematics |url=http://www.shawprize.org/en/shaw.php?tmp=3&twoid=53 |website=www.shawprize.org |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Crafoord Prize]] with [[James E. Gunn (astronomer)|James E. Gunn]] and [[Martin Rees]] (2005)<ref>{{cite web |title=The Crafoord Prize 2005 |url=https://www.crafoordprize.se/press_release/the-crafoord-prize-2005 |website=www.crafoordprize.se |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* Hitchcock Professorship (2006)<ref>{{cite web |title=Charles M. and Martha Hitchcock Lectures {{!}} Series {{!}} Berkeley Graduate Lectures |url=https://gradlectures.berkeley.edu/series/hitchcock/ |website=gradlectures.berkeley.edu |accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Dirac Medal]] (2013)<ref>{{cite web |title=FACULTY AWARD: Peebles awarded 2013 Dirac Medal for work in theoretical physics |url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2013/08/14/faculty-award-peebles-awarded-2013-dirac-medal-work-theoretical-physics |website=Princeton University |accessdate=October 8, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Member of the [[Order of Manitoba]] (2017)<ref>{{cite news |title=12 Manitobans to receive province's highest honour this summer |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/order-of-manitoba-recipients-1.4111916 |accessdate=October 8, 2019 |work=[[CBC.ca]] |date=May 12, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Nobel Prize in Physics]] (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/2019/summary/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physics 2019|publisher= [[Nobel Media AB]]|accessdate= October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n; Named after him\n* [[Asteroid]] [[18242 Peebles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rasc.ca/asteroid/18242 |title=Asteroid (18242) Peebles| author= |publisher=Royal Astronomical Society of Canada  |date=|accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Div col |colwidth=40em |small=yes}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Davis | first1 = M. | authorlink = Marc Davis (astronomer) | last2 = Peebles | first2 = P. J. E. | year = 1983 | title = A survey of galaxy redshifts. V \u2013 The two-point position and velocity correlations | url = | journal = Astrophys. J. | volume = 267 | issue = | page = 465 | doi=10.1086/160884 | bibcode=1983ApJ...267..465D}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Dicke | first1 = R. H. | authorlink4 = David Todd Wilkinson | last2 = Peebles | first2 = P. J. E. | last3 = Roll | first3 = P. G. | last4 = Wilkinson | first4 = D. T. | year = 1965 | title = Cosmic Black-Body Radiation | url = | journal = Astrophys. J. | volume = 142 | issue = | page = 414 | doi=10.1086/148306 | bibcode=1965ApJ...142..414D}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Fukugita | first1 = M. | last2 = Hogan | first2 = C. J. | last3 = Peebles | first3 = P. J. E. | year = 1998 | title = The cosmic baryon budget | journal = Astrophys. J. | volume = 503 | issue = 2| page = 518 | doi=10.1086/306025 | bibcode=1998ApJ...503..518F|arxiv = astro-ph/9712020 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Groth | first1 = E. J. | last2 = Peebles | first2 = P. J. E. | year = 1977 | title = Statistical Analysis Of Catalogs Of Extragalactic Objects. 7. Two And Three Point Correlation Functions For The High-Resolution Shane-Wirtanen Catalog Of Galaxies | url = | journal = Astrophys. J. | volume = 217 | issue = | page = 385 | doi=10.1086/155588 | bibcode=1977ApJ...